TRIP COMMENTS: Bird walk for Pine Hill Preserve group.  A little windy, but otherwise a great morning.  There were 18 of us on a very nice morning, with great views of the Sierra.  Highlights included a low flyby of an Osprey through the chaparral (!), a Swaison's Hawk (another out of place raptor), a Lewis's Woodpecker, a Gray Flycatcher seen by a few in the party and a couple of others singing, two Pacific-slope Flycatchers, several Ash-throated Flycatchers, a mini migration of Western Kingbirds over the high point in the chaparral, close looks at Hutton's Vireos, a Warbling Vireo, many Violet-green Swallows, an unexpected Red-breasted Nuthatch, several Blue-gray Gnatcatchers, many Wrentits and Orange-crowned Warblers, great looks at a singing Hermit Warbler, several Chipping Sparrows, a few Lark Sparrows, good scope views of several Sage Sparrows, a couple of Black-headed Grosbeaks, and a couple of Purple Finches. We also saw a Bramble Hairstreak (a small green butterfly common in the chaparral).

TRIP COMMENTS: After our visit to the refuge headquarters, Louis Bevier and I checked the shore of the Salton Sea from Obsidian Butte down to the intersection of Lack and Lindsey Roads.  Our primary target here was Yellow-footed Gull, though we did our best to check the shorebirds and gulls.  We did not spend much time scanning offshore, however, so our numbers for ducks and grebes in particular are probably little more than guesses.  We did not find many gulls at Obsidian Butte, but this is where we did see the vast majority of the pelicans and many of the cormorants.  Most of the gulls and shorebirds were instead on flats either north of Grubel Road or north of Lindsey Road.  There were a few high clouds, essentially calm conditions, and temperatures in the mid-60s.  11:55 am - 1:00 pm.----Between our check of the national wildlife refuge headquarters and our arrival at Obsidian Butte, we stopped briefly at the north end of Garst Road and then we scanned from the southwestern shore of Red Hill (ca. 11:15-11:30 am).  We did not search either site carefully and we found nothing of note at either site, so I have not included these birds in the list below (or, for that matter, in a separate list).

TRIP COMMENTS: Howard King, Bill Moramarco, and I spent about an hour scanning the shoreline and offshore waters along the seawall between the west end of Young Road and the south end of Obsidian Butte.  We worked from south to north to have the sun at the best angle.  We spent much of our time scanning offshore for an unusual duck, grebe, or loon, but we also checked the shorebirds and gulls on the flats.  Although we found good numbers of the expected species, we failed to find anything at all unusual.  It was clear, with a trace to mild (<5 knot) breeze from the north, and temperatures in the low to mid-60s.  9:20-10:30 am.

TRIP COMMENTS: Susan Steele and I spent the day checking the park and doing multiple loops around the lake for the local Christmas bird count.  In addition to checking the park for land birds, we had special permission to drive all the way around the lake, which allowed us to both scan the lake with the sun at a good angle and to see the back sides of the islands.  I also walked much of the north side of the lake checking the scrub along the shoreline, and we walked extensively around in the park, in which open lawns were interspersed with various species of trees (including many pines in addition to a variety of broad-leaf species).  I arrived at the park at 9:30 am, well after Susan, who arrived at 6:30 am and did at least one loop before I arrived.  I think we then did at least three complete loops of the lake together.  Much of our time late in the day was spent looking at the flock of gulls that came in to spend the night on the lake.  During the time I was present, it was clear yet rather hazy, but I understood that Susan encountered extensive ground fog for much of the early morning.  There was no more than a mild (<5 knot) breeze from the south, and temperatures seemed to range from the low to the mid-50s while I was present.  I was present from 9:30 am to 5:00 pm, but this list also includes those birds seen by Susan before I arrived.----California Ground-Squirrel - 30.

Observers: Bob Barnes, Scott Frazer. Temperature Range: 36F-55F. 33.3 miles driving roads in the Kern Water Bank plus 1 mile walking. Habitats: desert scrub, grasslands, open water, pastures, riparian strips, and wetlands. Most time spent counting wetland cells E1-2, N1-3 (dry), S1-2, S7-9, W1-6; plus numerous (11-15) unnamed dry cells and native habitat areas; plus at a few (2-4) unnamed wet cells. NOTE: As impressive as the species diversity and some of the numbers are, ONLY 30 of 120 (25%) cells were covered wholly or in part. The proverbial "surface was only scratched" applies here for our 12/16/11 coverage of this area. As John Sterling stated, it would take 7-8 good birders split up into 8 separate parties to cover this at least 30 square mile Kern Water Bank area in a single day.

Pico Rivera, confluence of San Gabriel River and San Jose Creek
TRIP COMMENTS: I joined Brian Daniels, Jon Dunn, Jon Feenstra, and Leo Ohtsuki on a search for a possible Blue-headed Vireo that was seen about a week earlier near the confluence of the San Gabriel River and San Jose Creek.  We parked at the equestrian center just below Peck Road and walked upstream along the southeastern bank of the San Gabriel River to San Jose Creek.  Although we concentrated our time checking the land birds in the riparian corridor right near the confluence of the two rivers, we looked at birds along our entire walk up the river and even a short distance up San Jose Creek.  We also scanned the waterbirds on the open water of both the river and the creek.  We found quite a few birds in the largest and most extensive thicket of willows located just below San Jose Creek and we found a number of Yellow-rumped Warblers in association with a few eucalyptus trees that were growing amid the riparian corridor downstream from the creek, but we never did see any vireos.  It was clear and initially calm, but with a mild (5 knot) breeze from the northeast coming up during our walk.  Temperatures probably increased from the upper 40s or low 50s to the low 60s during our visit.  7:10-8:45 am.

TRIP COMMENTS: Arrived early for the LA Audubon walk, but the group never showed up. Figured I''d gotten my wires crossed, so at 7:30 AM, I took off on my own.  This turned out to be fortuitous!  I went up Kiko''s trail, and instead of going left the way the group would have gone, I first went up the right hand trail to the crest.  There I found a Mountain Chickadee and a pair of Rufous-crowned Sparrow!  Then I retraced my steps, took the left hand trail and found the pair of California Gnatcatchers!  Also, at the base of the trail, I found a dead tree that housed on one side a Nuttall''s nest, on the other side a House Wren''s nest and at the hollow top, a beehive!

Given that we were not too far away, Howard King and I took a detour to the Los Angeles River to look for some Bobolinks that had been reported earlier in the week in the river channel above Willow Street.  We accessed the channel just above the bridge and then worked about 500 meters upstream checking a dense growth of tall vegetation that appeared to represent mostly annual herbs and grasses but also a few small willows.  There were also shallows and some mudflats in the area, but we did not see many waterbirds along this stretch of the river.  We located moderate numbers of cowbirds and smaller numbers of blackbirds and sparrows.  To better search the site, I walked down into the channel to flush the birds, and with some effort, we did manage to hear and briefly glimpse at least one and possibly two Bobolinks as they flushed from the grass and flew overhead.  It was clear, with a mild (5-10 knot) breeze, apparently from the northwest, and temperatures probably in the low 70s.  12:40-2:30 pm.----Dickcissel - 1 (?; I heard a single "bzzt" that sounded like the typical flight-call of a Dickcissel, but I was unable to see the bird as it went overhead).

Given that we were not too far away, Howard King and I took a detour to the Los Angeles River to look for some Bobolinks that had been reported earlier in the week in the river channel above Willow Street.  We accessed the channel just above the bridge and then worked about 500 meters upstream checking a dense growth of tall vegetation that appeared to represent mostly annual herbs and grasses but also a few small willows.  There were also shallows and some mudflats in the area, but we did not see many waterbirds along this stretch of the river.  We located moderate numbers of cowbirds and smaller numbers of blackbirds and sparrows.  To better search the site, I walked down into the channel to flush the birds, and with some effort, we did manage to hear and briefly glimpse at least one and possibly two Bobolinks as they flushed from the grass and flew overhead.  It was clear, with a mild (5-10 knot) breeze, apparently from the northwest, and temperatures probably in the low 70s.  12:40-2:30 pm.----Dickcissel - 1 (?; I heard a single "bzzt" that sounded like the typical flight-call of a Dickcissel, but I was unable to see the bird as it went overhead).

TRIP COMMENTS: Data collected with Birdwatcher's Diary (tm) for iPhone This is a SOS Survey for Virgin Creek Beach for August 19, 2011. There was one observer-Richard Hubacek. Time in: 0830 hrs. Time out: 1012 hrs. Tide was rising at end of survey. Weather was foggy with a slight breeze for most of survey. Sun came out at end of Survey. There were 5 people walking/jogging on wet sand. All other values were zero.  Shorebirds were very numerous during the survey. One unbanded (possible male) Snowy Plover was seen. Another Semipalmated Sandpiper was found. This was the third one, that I know of, found this year. Semipalmated Sandpipers are very rare. Based on reports from other areas that I've noted, Semipalmated Sandpipers are being found in greater numbers this year.

This count was done 1 week later because it was raining on our usual count--day. The weather and tide were ideal for counting birds though the temperature was chilly!!! The water was--very calm and still, with good reflections, and the heavy cloud layer prevented us from having to cope with any--glare from the sun. Due to the low tide, there were ample mud flats available and the birds made the most of--them. We spotted the Peregrine Falcon diving at the birds in the same area as last month, just north of the Big--Canyon area. Some of the ducks, avocets and shorebirds were changing into breeding plumage and two of the--Marbled Godwits were observed mating. Everyone on board got good views through Sallys scope of the--Eurasian Wigeon on the mudflat by the Big Canyon outflow. We enjoyed watching a huge flock of over 100--Black Skimmers in flight, a flock of 150+ Willets flew across the bay in front of us, and a large flock of Western--Sandpipers wheeled this way and that and then quickly settled two birds deep along the waters edge to feed.--On the island where the Black Skimmer decoys reside, we spotted some Western Meadowlarks in the grass.--It was a wonderful morning for birding, though it could have been a lot warmer!
Bob Hogan & Sharon Harrow

Boat Trip - Trip Leader: Nancy Kenyon Skipper: Tom Weiss Tide: High - outgoing--Birders who helped with the census: Jan Gaffney, Sharon Harrow, Nancy Kenyon, Chris Johnson,--Susan Munson. Comments: It was overcast and cold with no view of the sun until our return to the dock at--the end of the trip. Because of the stillness in the air, there were no raptors flying around except a Merlin which--dove into some vegetation, causing the birds to erupt in all directions. The Red-tailed Hawk we saw was--perched high in a palm tree and one of the Ospreys was on the nesting platform munching on a fish. We saw--2 kingfishers, one of which was perched on top of a pole on a boat, making an interesting silhouette. Many of--the American Avocets had striking cinnamon-colored heads and necks, the Double-crested Cormorants--sported white feather crests which contrasted nicely with their black heads, and a few of the Black-bellied--Plovers had black spots on their bellies. We saw some egrets flying over the pickleweed, their white wings--contrasting with the rusty-colored vegetation. Further up the bay, we saw some Marbled Godwits quite a--distance from shore, and at first we thought they were swimming out there until we realized they must be in a--shallow area and were simply wading as usual. We got great views of a large flock of Black Skimmers on a--mud flat. Usually, we see other boaters in the bay, but today we were the only ones; it was just too cold!

Boat Trip - Date: 4/20/11 Trip Leader: Nancy Kenyon Skipper: Tom Weiss Tide: Fairly low; incoming--Birders who helped with the census: Sally Menzel, Darrell Wilson, Nancy Kenyon, Chris Johnson, Pat--Vranicar, Deana Collins. Comments: The trip began under heavy clouds & a light rain mist which ceased--around 9:20. The water became absolutely still and we watched a solitary Snowy Egret stalking its prey at the--waters edge, perfectly reflected in the quiet water. This was ideal birding weather with soft light, no glare from--the sun, and still water. A huge gathering of Black Skimmers was on a mud flat along with large numbers of--Caspian, Elegant and Forsters Terns. When a low jet passed overhead, all the skimmers and terns became--airborne; it was quite a sight! Fortunately, they settled back down again and we were able to finish our count.--Some of the birds were in breeding plumage: an Eared Grebe with golden ear feathers, American Avocets--with cinnamon-colored heads & necks, one of the Black-bellied Plovers with a black belly, striking coloration on--the flanks and tail of a male Blue-winged Teal, a rich brown speckled pattern on the backs of the Long-billed--Curlews, and. . . the Willets which looked so different from the way we normally see them, that we didnt even--recognize them at first! (The Willets we normally see are plain grey, but these birds were speckled with a--warm brownish hue, and they didnt look like the Willets we knew at all, until they flew.) We saw a female--Mallard followed closely by 6 fuzzy ducklings and, at the Back Bay Science Center, we were thrilled to see 2--Osprey chicks on the nesting platform with one of the Osprey parents. Further on, we saw a brightly colored--male Hooded Oriole perched high in a palm tree and in the top of another palm tree, there was a Red-tailed--Hawk being harassed by 2 crows. It was a wonderful morning to be out birding!

The water became absolutely still and we watched a solitary Snowy Egret stalking its prey at the--waters edge, perfectly reflected in the quiet water. This was ideal birding weather with soft light, no glare from--the sun, and still water. A huge gathering of Black Skimmers was on a mud flat along with large numbers of--Caspian, Elegant and Forsters Terns. When a low jet passed overhead, all the skimmers and terns became--airborne; it was quite a sight! Fortunately, they settled back down again and we were able to finish our count.--Some of the birds were in breeding plumage: an Eared Grebe with golden ear feathers, American Avocets--with cinnamon-colored heads & necks, one of the Black-bellied Plovers with a black belly, striking coloration on--the flanks and tail of a male Blue-winged Teal, a rich brown speckled pattern on the backs of the Long-billed--Curlews, and. . . the Willets which looked so different from the way we normally see them, that we didnt even--recognize them at first! (The Willets we normally see are plain grey, but these birds were speckled with a--warm brownish hue, and they didnt look like the Willets we knew at all, until they flew.) We saw a female--Mallard followed closely by 6 fuzzy ducklings and, at the Back Bay Science Center, we were thrilled to see 2--Osprey chicks on the nesting platform with one of the Osprey parents. Further on, we saw a brightly colored--male Hooded Oriole perched high in a palm tree and in the top of another palm tree, there was a Red-tailed--Hawk being harassed by 2 crows. It was a wonderful morning to be out birding!

TRIP COMMENTS: Boat Trip - Date: 5/18/11 Trip Leader: Nancy Kenyon Skipper: Tom Weiss Tide: medium--Birders: Bonny Ahern, Barbara Demory, Carol Freund, Sheila Harlow, Terry Hill, Chris Johnson,--Karen & Ed Johnston, Nancy Kenyon, Chuck Nichols, Merle & Alice Whitney, and Darrell Wilson.--Comments: The weather was cloudy and cold, more like a winter day. It was quite evident that most--of the regularly seen birds had left the area and flown north to their nesting grounds because there--was not a single bird on any of the mud flats. The few shorebirds we did see were flying. The terns--were active and noisy, flying up and down the channel and calling raucously. In recent months we--have not had any Brown Pelicans, so it was nice to see 7 of them on this trip. Last month, the Osprey--nesting platform at the Back Bay Science Center was inhabited, but today it was empty and the--young Ospreys had apparently fledged. We saw one Osprey perched on the face of a steep slope--above the bay which is not a usual location for this species. A Northern Harrier was observed--carrying a stick. Since Harriers seldom nest here in the county, this sighting was of great interest to--us and we wondered if the Harriers had found a good nesting site somewhere near the bay. The--swallows were active, darting back and forth across the channel in pursuit of insects. We were--surprised to see that a Says Phoebe was still in the area. The wind picked up on our return trip,--dropping the temperature considerably and making it difficult to hear any birds singing. The few birds--we did see on our return trip were hunkered down.

Boat Trip - Date: 6/15/11 Trip Leader: Nancy Kenyon Skippers: Nancy Thompson & Tom Weiss--Tide: high. Birders who conducted the count: Nancy Kenyon, Sally Menzel, Deana Collins,--Darrell Wilson, Chuck Nichols & Kurt Miethke.--Comments: The sky was completely overcast with gray clouds and a cool mist. The water was very--still and we enjoyed seeing perfect reflections at the water¿s edge. Few boats were out so we had the--bay to ourselves and the birds. The main birding activity centered around the Caspian, Forster¿s, and--Least Terns flying up and down, diving into the water for fish, and calling raucously. The tide was--high and we were able to spot, as well as hear, a couple of Clapper Rails as they scurried across an--opening in the reeds. The Great Blue Herons were hunched down in the cordgrass like blue-gray--stumps, but the egrets were actively stalking their prey. We were surprised to find so many Northern--Harriers, a species not usually that abundant here in the summer. One the harriers, which was--perched way out in the marsh, gave us lots of trouble identifying it because of the deep reddish hue--on its breast; when it flew, however, there was no doubt about its identity. Another surprise was--seeing so many shorebirds: 24 Willets, 6 Marbled Godwits, 2 Least Sandpipers, a Whimbrel, a Longbilled--Curlew, and 8 Black-bellied Plovers, some of which were in partial breeding plumage. Sally--spotted 2 Red-crowned Parrots flying by and Kurt found an Ash-throated Flycatcher. The Savannah--Sparrows in the cordgrass along the shore were quite vocal, and on the hillside, the House Finches,--Common Yellowthroats, and Northern Mockingbirds were singing. It was a wonderful morning!

Boat Trip - Date: 7/20/11 Trip Leader: Nancy Kenyon Skipper: Eric Walther--Tide: incoming. Birders who conducted the count: Nancy Kenyon, Deana Collins, Darrell Wilson,--Chuck Nichols & Greg Griffin.--Comments: The morning started out completely overcast, but the clouds dissipated as we progressed further--up the bay. When we returned to the area near the Sea Base, we were surprised the fog had not lifted there at--all. During the first hour, we had the bay to ourselves and the birds, the water was relatively still with only faint--ripples on it from the morning breeze, and the birds were pretty quiet. The shorebirds were in full to partial--breeding plumage, so we used body shape & bill length to differentiate the species rather than using their--colors & plumage patterns. One of the godwits had large splotches of brown on its body which really made it--look strange. We had a little difficulty identifying one of the Great Blue Herons because he was hunched way--down in the cordgrass at the water¿s edge. We saw a large crab sunning itself on the shore and further on we--saw five of the Black Skimmers sitting on a mudflat, their black & white bodies and bright orange legs & feet--making a stunning contrast with the dark mud. We heard a few of the Willets calling and the call notes of the--Greater Yellowlegs reverberated throughout the marsh. The Least Terns were actively diving into the water--and the Caspian & Forster¿s Terns were flying up and down the channel. We found a brightly colored inflatable--beach ball floating in the water and everyone agreed it needed to be removed, so Eric skillfully maneuvered--the boat in the right position and Chuck was able to pluck it from the water. In one area, the cordgrass at the--water¿s edge was festooned with large batches of white-colored dead algae which had been washed up during--high tide. On a distant post in the water, we spotted an Osprey eating a fish and at closer range we saw one of--the clean-looking Western Gulls perched on a buoy. It was a great morning to be out on the bay.

From the PCH parking lot at 0615 (59° F; light drizzle, calm), I walked to the Outer Bolsa Bay (2.5 ft low tide at 9:40) fore shorebirds on the mud flats. I returned to the "point" overlook of the Big Bay (or Full Tidal Basin) working shorebirds on the south edge of Rabbit Island. I joined Leo Ohtsuki at the "point" overlook and scanned as best I could the shorebirds on the far side of the Big Bay. We left at 0930 (64° F; cloudy but calm).

Brian Leatherman, Leo Ohtsuki, and I went to the east side of the park to look for the Lucy’s Warbler. It was terribly crowded due to Civil War Days, so I immediately bolted for the west side of the park. Brian and Leo gave it a shot, but didn’t find the LUWA or anything else and soon joined me on the west side of the park where I wasn’t finding any migrants either. However, Huntington Lake produced some interesting birds.
SPECIES COMMENTS: perched on sycamore near DCCO nests

[Notes and comments by Curtis Marantz] Brian Daniels, Jon Dunn, Jim Pike, Tom Benson, and I (Curtis Marantz) were spotters on the annual fall pelagic birding trip sponsored by the Sea and Sage Audubon Society aboard the Ocean Institute's R/V Sea Explorer.  Both on our departure and on our return we cruised slowly through the Dana Point Harbor scanning the breakwaters and birds inside the harbor itself for anything unusual.  We checked the main breakwater a little more carefully on our way out, but I suspect many of the same birds were present on our return (though there seemed to be more pelicans and Heermann's Gulls on our way back to port).  There was a low marine layer, little wind, and temperatures in the low 60s on our departure (7:15-7:30 am), but somewhat higher clouds with some blue sky, a mild breeze, and temperatures probably in the middle to upper 60s upon our return to port (12:55-1:10 pm).

Started with 7 kayaks, 8 people. About 11:45, four kayaks and 5 people left. Remaining three people paddled much further up the bay before returning to original launch point, Newport Aquatic Center.  Sunny, 70 degrees, light wind, unusually high tide (over 6 feet), which swamped much marshland that is normally above water.  Shorebirds were scarce because their mud flats were all submerged. American Kestrel was the bird of the day, acting Northern Harrier-like, swooping over partly indundated weed beds to opportunistically grab small prey that had climbed the stalks of the weeds. Saw one group of three Kestrels flying together - noticeable white band at end of tail feathers.  At the end of the outing, as tide ebbed near Newport Aquatic Center, the distant opposite bank of the channel had exposed mud margins and a large number of shorebird species feeding. The day's only Black Skimmers were resting among those shorebirds.

Sunny, 70 degrees, light wind, unusually high tide (over 6 feet), which swamped much marshland that is normally above water.  Shorebirds were scarce because their mud flats were all submerged. American Kestrel was the bird of the day, acting Northern Harrier-like, swooping over partly indundated weed beds to opportunistically grab small prey that had climbed the stalks of the weeds. Saw one group of three Kestrels flying together - noticeable white band at end of tail feathers.  At the end of the outing, as tide ebbed near Newport Aquatic Center, the distant opposite bank of the channel had exposed mud margins and a large number of shorebird species feeding. The day's only Black Skimmers were resting among those shorebirds.

TRIP COMMENTS: Boat Trip - We saw an enormous flock of Western Sandpipers. Chris Johnson spotted the Goldeneye and--Barbara Demory photographed it, helping us to confirm its identification. Several of the Red-tailed Hawks were--perched on the ground, partially obscured in the grass, their colors blending with the warm brown of the grass.--One of the Red-tails was eating something while another was perched on a low post, being harassed by a--swooping Northern Harrier. We also saw 3 White-tailed Kites. One was perched on top of a yucca, while the--others were flying around, actively hunting for food. We missed the Eurasian Wigeon at Big Canyon, but did--spot the wintering Loggerhead Shrike perched on some high vegetation within sight of the water.

Howard King and I spent the morning at the San Jacinto Wildlife Area, where we did a moderately thorough search of the middle part of the refuge, as accessed mostly on foot.  Due to flooding, we did not drive into the new wetland complex.  We nevertheless walked around the most northeastern ponds of the new complex, along the San Jacinto River corridor, and around the back ponds in the northern part of the refuge.  We did not have any specific targets today, yet we had one of the best days I have ever had at the refuge, given our encountering a combination of most of the species known to be wintering here and a few new ones.  We spent as much time searching for land birds as anything else, but I did not really try to count the waterbirds carefully (though our limited coverage of the duck club ponds likely resulted in our missing many of the birds that were present).  Although numbers of waterbirds on the refuge seemed lower than they had been, huge numbers of birds on Mystic Lake suggested that many birds were still in the general area.  The deciduous trees were still mostly leafless, though some were beginning to leaf out.  It was mostly clear apart from a few high, thin clouds, initially calm but with a mild (<5 knot) breeze late in our visit, and temperatures probably increasing from the low 50s to the middle 60s (or possibly the upper 60s).  7:30-11:30 am.----Coyote - 1 (I missed one seen by Howard);--California Ground-Squirrel - 6.

Howard King and I joined Doug Karalun, Dave Furseth, and briefly also Brad Singer and Vic Muryama, to look for a Tufted Duck that was reported earlier in the day at Lake Perris by Paul Clarke and Cathy McFadden.  Others were looking at the bird when we arrived, so we had little difficulty finding the duck in the bay just off the beach east of parking lot 1; however, we realized almost as quickly that the bird was a hybrid rather than a pure Tufted Duck.  After studying this bird and the other ducks along the northwestern shore, we also scanned the lake from the northeastern end to see if we could relocate the Little Gull that we had seen flying in this direction earlier in the day.  Unfortunately, most of the gulls here were a bit too distant for us to have easily identified the Little Gull, and we found nothing else of note during our brief stop.  Our search of the lake was therefore quite superficial and we spent almost no time at all looking for land birds.  It was partly cloudy, with the clouds high and thin, a mild (5-10 knot) breeze, apparently from the west, and temperatures probably in the middle to upper 60s.  11:45 am - 1:00 pm.----California Ground-Squirrel - 10.

Chet McGaugh, Howard King, and I spent the morning checking the Whitewater River delta and the Torres Martinez Wetlands ponds.  We were unable to get a ride out to the end of the road, so we walked out to the delta from the gate along the levee road off Lincoln Street, and along the way we checked briefly the land birds in the desert scrub and those in the riparian corridor along the river.  The willows are now of moderate size and the riparian corridor in general is looking quite good for both breeding and migrant species typical of riparian habitats.  Upon reaching the delta, we checked the now extensive flats and the waters of the bays both east and west of the delta.  In an effort to locate a singing redstart in willows out at the end of the delta, I crossed the Whitewater River.  Rather than wading back across the river, I continued west along the shoreline to the ponds.  I checked the two southern ponds carefully.  The southernmost pond had shallows, extensive flats, and islands that looked good for shorebirds, but the only species present were stilts and a few Killdeer.  The next pond to the north had some flats, but it also had a bit more water and several snags on which cormorants and herons were roosting.  I scanned the cormorants carefully, and I also checked the cattail thickets around the edges of this pond.  I met Chet and Howard at the tent along the eastern edge of the ponds, so I did not check the smaller and more densely vegetated ponds in the northern part of the site.  It was clear all morning and essentially calm early, but with a mild (5 knot) breeze that varied in direction from the north to the south or the southwest that came up mid-morning.  Temperatures were quite mild for this site in early June, ranging from the mid-50s to only the upper 80s to low 90s by the time we left the area just before noon.  6:30-11:45 am.----Royal Tern - 1 (?, calling; I thought I heard calls by either this species or Elegant Tern and then saw at great distance, and mostly as it flew away, a heavy-bodied tern that appeared to have an orange bill and mostly white underwings with the black seemingly restricted to the trailing edges of the primaries);--Desert Cottontail - 12.

John Luther drove up yesterday afternoon and stayed overnight.  We went out to the pit about 7:25 a.m. but before going out I had a minimum of 70 LARK SPARROWS in the area by the back gate, setting an all-time record for my yard.  It was about 51F when we started with no breeze and a completely overcast sky.  By the time we ended it was mostly sunny and about 61F.----Louise McCullough and Gil Ewing joined us about 8 a.m. and we headed to the pond overlook since Louise needed Hooded Merganser for the county.  We actually all got to see him on the far side.  Gill picked up HARRIS''S SPARROW for March and Louise probably saw it when she and Gill walked back to the pit while John and I walked down to the Gristmill overlook and back.----John and I also saw the Slate-colored Fox Sparrow and an adult Puget Sound White-crowned Sparrow.----We had a huge flock of swallows on the other side of the river.  We must have identified about 35 over the morning as Tree Swallows but could not be sure if any of the distant flock had any Violet-green Swallows, which I often see in numbers along the river on rainy days.----The Merlin blasted past so I could not be sure if it was the usual Taiga race.----Lots of birds were checking the nest boxes.----Great morning

The "Peregrine" was a light, definite brown, without the vertical streaks I expect in a young bird. A fellow birder with a scope was sure it was a Peregrine, yet when it flew up, I thought it had black under the wings. It made me wonder if it was a Prairie Falcon, which I don''t expect by the coast. But because of my vision problems, and the fact that the falcon was backlit, I can''t say 100% certainty that there was black; but the other birder also remarked on the light brown color.

TRIP COMMENTS: My neighbor called me outside to look at a hawk, which turned out to be an Osprey, circling around and then going off to the north. Three of our Red-shouldered Hawks were around, including the one with the voice problem. A mockingbird did a very creditable imitation of his squeak. I had thought before that this hawk was a male, and today it is confirmed, because inspite of the voice problem, he mated with a female. My guess is that they''re an established couple from last year. Today they were in the eucalyptus to the east, but the other days I saw them to the west and south of this property, so I don''t actually know where their territory is centered. But I want to keep an eye on them and how they''re doing. The other exciting bird was the Cassin''s Vireo, in the same area where I saw one in the spring, so I wonder if it is the same bird.

TRIP COMMENTS: Paul Lehman, Howard King, and I next visited Lower Otay Reservoir, where we had hoped to see a Lesser Black-backed Gull that Paul found here on 4 February, and several land birds, all of which had been present since 9 January.  Although we spent much of our time scanning the gulls on the lake and those loafing on the docks, we did wander along the parking lot in search of Nashville, Chestnut-sided, and Palm Warblers that had been frequenting several lerp-infested eucalyptus trees that were growing along the parking lot to the south of the boat launch and even further south along a trail that followed the shore of the lake.  The nearby terrain was covered with Coastal Sage-scrub, but we did not find many birds at all in this habitat.  In fact, most of the land birds that we did find were either in the eucalyptus trees or in the scrub between these trees and the shore of the lake.  We did manage to find all three warblers (though only Paul saw the Nashville) and we eventually located the Lesser Black-backed Gull amid an interesting concentration of birds, most of which appeared at the lake only after noon, but we never did find a Clay-colored Sparrow that had also been seen here intermittently.  Matt Sadowski and Christine Harvey were present before we arrived, but several others, whose names I did not get, were also present during the course of our visit.  It was mostly to partly cloudy, with a mild to moderate (10+ knot) breeze from the southwest, and temperatures that were probably in the upper 50s to the low 60s.  Howard and I were here 9:35-10:30 am, and again, 1:00-2:45 pm; however, Paul and most of the others remained here during the two-and-a-half-hours that we were gone, and Matt, Christine, and others arrived in the morning up to an hour before we did.  Given that we consulted with Paul for this list, which essentially includes everything seen over the entire period he was at the lake, it is not surprising that I missed a number of the birds seen today.----California Ground-Squirrel - 1.

I was up there for over two hours and Sharpies were definitely moving through. I counted only ones obviously heading north toward the gate and only after they had passed my position on the battery (as virtually all of them were.) A couple did appear to veer off to the east once past the Battery so they may have doubled back but most of them seemed to cross the gate. They were mostly coming through in singles though a couple of times I had 3-4 in view at once.----more interesting was that a immature Rough-legged Hawk was reported on the Rare Bird Hotline an hour after my sighting from SF, from the Marin side of the gate by Tim Behr of GGRO and that his bird was flying back over to SF. Maybe the same bird just decided to cross the gate a couple of times? weird

As part of the San Francisco CBC, we birded an area of bayside locations including these hotspots: Oyster Pt., SF Bay Trail--San Bruno Pt., SF Bay Trail--Haskins Way, SamTrans Marsh--north, Colma Creek Mouth, and SamTrans Marsh. We also covered the shore of the water treatment facility next to the airport, just south of SamTrans Marsh, which does not have a hotspot location. We covered about 5 miles on foot and an additional 2 miles by car to get around to bayside locations. Because the primary birding happened on foot, we listed the mileage accordingly. However, we did add a couple of species seen en route to our on foot locations (we stopped the car to make good observations of these).

Tracking it down, I was hoping for something more unusual, but we had good looks at a Yellow Warbler!  Quite a surprize this early in the year.  The bird was seen very well; dark eye on a plain face, yellow on the underside of the recs all the way to the tail tip.  Very familiar with this species and other species likely to be confused with it.  Not an Orange-crowned Warbler.  I don''t believe I''ve ever seen one in winter before, though they are very occasionally reported.

LOCALITY: Pt. Mugu Naval Air Station (restricted access)
TRIP COMMENTS: Birds recorded during Thousand Oaks CBC.  Surveyed nearly entire base including Mugu Lagoon (mouth and causeway), marshes in restricted area, perimeter road along edges of gun clubs, residential neighborhoods and adjacent areas, ballfields, old golf course, airfields, and beaches.----Conditions were clear and cool, with temps starting in high 40s and peaking in mid-60s. Fog moved in off the ocean in the afternoon and reduced visibility dramatically. We repeatedly covered many areas and did cover nearly all of the installation's 4,500 acres.----All birding by one party; myself, Todd McGrath and Don DesJardin.

Continuing migrant group of Western Grebes in deep water turning basin

Continuing Aechmophorus grebe flock, all Westerns, differentiated from Clark''s based on major field marks.  This flock has been present in the deep water turning basin at the Port of Sacramento for several weeks now.  Today was the first day I noted courtship behaviors between two pairs.  This seems an unlikely spot for breeding, and I have suspected for several weeks now that this aggregation is in a pre-breeding staging area, however parts of the adjacent marsh could be appropriate for breeding, though water levels are extremely high right now. Given high water levels across the region, this group could also represent birds pushed out of other areas.
